  "text": "## Kubernetes Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling\n\nKubernetes implements comprehensive SIGTERM/SIGINT handling across multiple layers:\n\n**Signal Registration (kubernetes/kubernetes):**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go` contains the core `SetupSignalContext()` function which registers for SIGTERM and SIGINT using a buffered channel with capacity 2\n- `signal_posix.go` defines `shutdownSignals = []os.Signal{os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM}` for Unix systems\n- `signal_windows.go` handles Windows-specific signal handling with `os.Interrupt` only\n- The implementation ensures only one signal handler can exist (uses a channel to enforce this)\n\n**Shutdown Mechanism:**\n- First signal cancels the context, allowing graceful shutdown\n- Second signal forces immediate exit with code 1\n- `cmd/kube-apiserver/app/server.go` calls `SetupSignalContext()` early and passes the context through the command setup to `NewAPIServerCommand()`\n\n**Lifecycle Management:**\n- `lifecycle_signals.go` tracks 8 lifecycle events: ShutdownInitiated, AfterShutdownDelayDuration, PreShutdownHooksStopped, NotAcceptingNewRequest, InFlightRequestsDrained, HTTPServerStoppedListening, HasBeenReady, and MuxAndDiscoveryComplete\n- The shutdown sequence follows this order: stop accepting requests, drain in-flight requests, then stop server\n- `genericapiserver.go` uses the signal context with `RunWithContext(ctx)` to monitor for cancellation\n\n**Testing:**\n- `genericapiserver_graceful_termination_test.go` validates graceful termination with both keep-listening-disabled and enabled modes\n- `graceful_shutdown_test.go` tests HTTP/2 stream handling during shutdown\n\n## Prometheus Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling\n\nPrometheus uses `oklog/run.Group` pattern with explicit signal handling:\n\n**Signal Registration (prometheus/prometheus):**\n- `cmd/prometheus/main.go` contains: `term := make(chan os.Signal, 1)` and `signal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)` in the termination handler\n- The handler listens for three shutdown triggers: OS signals, web service requests via `webHandler.Quit()`, or internal cancellation\n- When a signal arrives, it logs 'Received an OS signal, exiting gracefully...' with the signal name\n\n**Shutdown Sequence:**\n- Closes the `reloadReady` channel to unblock dependent goroutines\n- Sets web handler status to `web.Stopping`\n- Adds shutdown notification via `notifs.AddNotification(notifications.ShuttingDown)`\n- Components shut down in coordinated order: reload manager → discovery managers → rule manager → scrape manager → storage\n\n**Web Handler Integration:**\n- `web/web.go` provides a `Quit()` method returning `<-chan struct{}` for external shutdown requests\n- When lifecycle APIs are enabled (`/-/quit` endpoint), closing this channel triggers graceful shutdown\n- Uses `sync.Once` to ensure only one quit request succeeds\n\n## Grafana Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling\n\nGrafana implements graceful shutdown through context-based coordination:\n\n**Shutdown Mechanism (grafana/grafana):**\n- `pkg/server/server.go` contains the `Shutdown(ctx context.Context, reason string)` method that initiates graceful shutdown\n- Uses `sync.Once` via `shutdownOnce` to ensure shutdown runs exactly once, preventing race conditions\n- Implements timeout handling: if context deadline expires before shutdown completes, logs 'Timed out while waiting for server to shut down'\n- Delegates to `managerAdapter.Shutdown(ctx, \"shutdown\")` to stop all background services\n\n**HTTP Server Graceful Shutdown:**\n- `pkg/api/http_server.go` implements the `Run()` method with graceful shutdown via context cancellation\n- When context is cancelled, spawns a goroutine that calls `hs.httpSrv.Shutdown(context.Background())`\n- Gracefully handles server closure: if `errors.Is(err, http.ErrServerClosed)` returns, logs success instead of propagating error\n- Supports certificate reload with periodic watching without server restart\n\n**Systemd Integration:**\n- Includes `notifySystemd()` method that sends 'READY=1' to systemd on startup\n\n## Comparative Analysis\n\n**Shutdown Timeout Implementations:**\n- Kubernetes: Uses context with explicit signal sequencing (first signal → graceful, second → immediate)\n- Prometheus: Relies on oklog/run.Group error propagation to drive shutdown\n- Grafana: Uses context deadlines passed to Shutdown method for timeout control\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- Kubernetes: Enforces strict lifecycle signal ordering (NotAcceptingNewRequest → InFlightRequestsDrained → HTTPServerStoppedListening)\n- Prometheus: Manager-based ordering through run.Group (reload → discovery → rules → scrape → storage)\n- Grafana: Delegates to managerAdapter for service-level cleanup coordination\n\n**Connection Draining:**\n- Kubernetes: Explicitly tracks InFlightRequestsDrained signal after NotAcceptingNewRequest\n- Prometheus: oklog/run.Group coordinates component dependencies\n- Grafana: Relies on http.Server.Shutdown() built-in behavior for connection draining\n"
}

